Logged Wages: A Simple Model in Stan

Let’s do a simple model as a proof of concept. We want to predict the logged wages of skilled foreign workers, conditioning on where they went to school, what country they came from, and the size of the employer for key predictors. (We do this the Bayesian way using Stan.) The model may look something like…

wage ~ emp_size + fw_edu + fw_edu_name

Expose some Stan functions…

rstan::expose_stan_functions("quantile_functions.stan")
## Trying to compile a simple C file
source("GLD_helpers.R")

Set up the priors…

m_alpha <- log(100000) # Normal prior stuff for alpha. Mean.
s_alpha <- 0.15 # Standard deviation.

# GLD priors for coefficients...
medians <- c(ES = 0.05, E = 0.06, S = 0.10) # ES employer's size, E education, S school.
lowers <- c(ES = 0.03, E = 0.03, S = 0.07)
uppers <- c(ES = 0.07, E = 0.09, S = 0.13)
ninety <- c(ES = 0.10, E = 0.11, S = 0.15)
a_s <- lapply(1:length(medians), FUN = function(i) {
  GLD_solver(lowers[i], medians[i], uppers[i], ninety[i], alpha = 0.9)
  }) # Some warnings about bounded tails.
names(a_s) <- names(medians)


# JQPDS prior stuff for sigma...
q_sigma <- c(lower = 0.25, median = 0.5, upper = 1) # Quantiles / What I think.

We do some recoding on the data to speed up the evaluation. We want to further recode the education levels to something ordered, going from Bachelor’s, through Master’s, and PhD. Insofar as the schools go, we divvy the set up into four tiers, roughly, depending on the league tables: (i) Not-in-Ranking/Lowest Tier, (ii) U.S. Lower Tier, (iii) U.S. Middle Tier, and (iv) U.S. Ivies. We shall hone in on the schools with 1000 graduates or more (from among the foreign workers in the dataset). These are…

Model Matrix

Now, we’re ready to set up our model.matrix()…

# Set up the X matrix and center it...
X <- model.matrix(log(wage) ~ emp_size + fw_edu + fw_edu_name,
                  data = d.sub.c)[ , -1] # Drop the intercept because we handle it ourselves.

X <- sweep(X, MARGIN = 2, STATS = colMeans(X), FUN = `-`) # Center the columns.

Prior Predictive Distribution (PPD)

Drawing from the PPD…

# Ready to draw from the prior predictive distribution (PPD) of log-wages...
PPD <- replicate(1000, {
  alpha_ <- rnorm(1, mean = m_alpha, sd = s_alpha)
  
  beta_ES_ <- GLD_rng(medians["ES"], IQR = uppers["ES"] - lowers["ES"], asymmetry = a_s$ES[1], steepness = a_s$ES[2])
  beta_E_ <- GLD_rng(medians["E"], IQR = uppers["E"] - lowers["E"], asymmetry = a_s$E[1], steepness = a_s$E[2])
  beta_S_ <- GLD_rng(medians["S"], IQR = uppers["S"] - lowers["S"], asymmetry = a_s$S[1], steepness = a_s$S[2])
  
  mu_ <- alpha_ + beta_ES_ * X[ , "emp_size"] + beta_E_ * X[ , "fw_edu"] + # Priors on the coefficients.
         beta_S_ * X[ , "fw_edu_name"]
  
  sigma_ <- JQPDS_rng(lower_bound = 0, alpha = 0.25, quantiles = q_sigma) # Drawn from a normal distribution.
  
  epsilon_ <- rnorm(length(mu_), mean = 0, sd = sigma_) # Some error term.
  
  y_ <- mu_ + epsilon_
  y_
})
# round(quantile(c(exp(PPD)), probs = 1:9 / 10), digits = 3)

Prior Distribution

Drawing from the prior…

# Prior (not predictive) distribution...
R_squared <- replicate(1000, {
  alpha_ <- rnorm(1, mean = m_alpha, sd = s_alpha)
  
  beta_ES_ <- GLD_rng(medians["ES"], IQR = uppers["ES"] - lowers["ES"], asymmetry = a_s$ES[1], steepness = a_s$ES[2])
  beta_E_ <- GLD_rng(medians["E"], IQR = uppers["E"] - lowers["E"], asymmetry = a_s$E[1], steepness = a_s$E[2])
  beta_S_ <- GLD_rng(medians["S"], IQR = uppers["S"] - lowers["S"], asymmetry = a_s$S[1], steepness = a_s$S[2])
  
  mu_ <- alpha_ + beta_ES_ * X[ , "emp_size"] + beta_E_ * X[ , "fw_edu"] + # Priors on the coefficients.
         beta_S_ * X[ , "fw_edu_name"]
  
  sigma_ <- JQPDS_rng(lower_bound = 0, alpha = 0.25, quantiles = q_sigma) # Drawn from a normal distribution.
  
  numer <- var(mu_)
  denom <- sigma_^2 + numer
  R_squared <- numer / denom
  R_squared
})
# summary(R_squared)

Posterior Distribution

Using stan_lm() to draw from the posterior…

post <- stan_lm(log(wage) ~ emp_size + fw_edu + fw_edu_name, data = d.sub.c,
                prior = R2(location = median(R_squared), what = "median"),
                prior_intercept = normal(location = m_alpha, scale = s_alpha, autoscale = FALSE))
